<subSubSection id="D4DF6509FFE8B921FF6FA937FD6FF862" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="9C7A3682FFE8B921FF6FA937FD94F9C1" blockId="18.[192,1440,1057,1242]" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis id="AEB1EA90FFE8B921FF6FA937FEDCF922" bold="true" box="[192,372,1057,1081]" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Distribution.</emphasis>
The species is known only from 
<collectingRegion id="5E01F860FFE8B921FCBFA934FCC2F921" box="[784,874,1058,1082]" country="United States of America" name="Florida" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Florida</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion id="5E01F860FFE8B921FC05A934FC5BF922" box="[938,1011,1058,1081]" country="United States of America" name="Texas" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Texas</collectingRegion>
in the 
<collectingCountry id="E4D27612FFE8B921FBE0A934FB54F921" box="[1103,1276,1058,1082]" name="United States of America" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">United States</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation id="04FE2A07FFE8B921FAA1A934FAC0F921" box="[1294,1384,1058,1082]" captionStart="Figure 22" captionStartId="31.[192,276,1827,1849]" captionTargetBox="[192,1440,192,1718]" captionTargetId="figure-20@31.[192,1440,192,1091]" captionTargetPageId="31" captionText="Figure 22. North American distribution of Lionothus bidentatus (black circles), L. exiguus (black triangles), L. parvoculus (black squares)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5193732" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5193732/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Fig. 22</figureCitation>
). Its distribution in the extreme south of 
<collectingRegion id="5E01F860FFE8B921FD22A954FD7EF942" box="[653,726,1090,1113]" country="United States of America" name="Texas" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Texas</collectingRegion>
suggests that the species may also occur in 
<collectingCountry id="E4D27612FFE8B921FAA6A954FACBF941" box="[1289,1379,1090,1114]" name="Mexico" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Mexico</collectingCountry>
. The Florida populations seem to be disjunct from those in Texas. They may have once been connected across the Gulf Coastal Plain at times of Pleistocene low sea levels. This was a route from a western source for faunas moving into Florida, and is recognized for the movement of both vertebrates (
<bibRefCitation id="F8544B73FFE8B921FAA2A9B4FA30F9A1" author="Webb, S. D." bookContentInfo="765 p." box="[1293,1432,1186,1210]" editor="R. L. Myers &amp; J. J. Ewel" journalOrPublisher="University of Central Florida Press; Orlando, FL" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" pagination="70 - 100" refId="ref19300" refString="Webb, S. D. 1990. Historical biogeography. p. 70 - 100. In: R. L. Myers and J. J. Ewel (eds.). Ecosystems of Florida. University of Central Florida Press; Orlando, FL. 765 p." title="Historical biogeography" type="book chapter" volumeTitle="Ecosystems of Florida" year="1990">Webb 1990</bibRefCitation>
) and arthropods (
<bibRefCitation id="F8544B73FFE8B921FE23A9D4FD87F9C1" author="Deyrup, M. A." box="[396,559,1218,1242]" journalOrPublisher="Florida Scientist" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" pagination="254 - 271" part="52" refId="ref18206" refString="Deyrup, M. A. 1989. Arthropods endemic to Florida scrub. Florida Scientist 52: 254 - 271." title="Arthropods endemic to Florida scrub" type="journal article" year="1989">Deyrup 1989</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9C7A3682FFE8B921FF6FA817FBFFF801" blockId="18.[192,1111,1281,1306]" box="[192,1111,1281,1306]" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis id="AEB1EA90FFE8B921FF6FA817FEC0F802" bold="true" box="[192,360,1281,1305]" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Seasonality.</emphasis>
Adults are known only from the months of March to August.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9C7A3682FFE8B921FF6FA857FD6FF862" blockId="18.[192,1440,1345,1402]" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis id="AEB1EA90FFE8B921FF6FA857FEF1F842" bold="true" box="[192,345,1345,1369]" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Bionomics.</emphasis>
Adults are known from mesic forests, thorn thicket, and palm forest, often on sandy soils. All were collected in flight intercept traps.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="D4DF6509FFE8B921FF6FA8B4FBFBF8A1" box="[192,1107,1442,1466]" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="9C7A3682FFE8B921FF6FA8B4FBFBF8A1" blockId="18.[192,1107,1442,1466]" box="[192,1107,1442,1466]" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis id="AEB1EA90FFE8B921FF6FA8B4FEF4F8A1" bold="true" box="[192,348,1442,1466]" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Etymology.</emphasis>
Latin “ 
<taxonomicName id="5BC54D01FFE8B921FE16A8B4FDBEF8A2" authorityName="Peck and Cook" authorityYear="2013" box="[441,534,1442,1465]" class="Insecta" family="Leiodidae" genus="Lionothus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="exiguus">
<emphasis id="AEB1EA90FFE8B921FE16A8B4FDBEF8A2" box="[441,534,1442,1465]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">exiguus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
”, small, refers to the small size of this species.
</paragraph>
